narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Weekly readings teach you about gamelans context in Indonesian culture and class time is spent playing the instruments

one of the best courses I've taken at Yale - this is truly a gem of a class. Class time is essentially all rehearsing and a lot of fun. It's not stressful and very little work. I learned how to play at least 4 different instruments, and I got to really study Indonesia.
Absolutely take this class! One of the best classes I've taken at Yale! So fun and a cant miss experience.

This is a great class! You should definitely take it! It's super fun and really different from other classes. There's a fair amount of reading and writing that goes along with the music, but it's worth it!
An opportunity to learn about an intricate foreign culture

I would definitely recommend this class! You end up learning a lot about Indonesian culture and the interplay between religion and the arts. We had a weekly reading (about 10 pages) and video, with some short reading responses (just a couple of sentences each). This class was also a LOT of fun. Playing the gamelan is relaxing, even though it sounds a little weird at first.

Gamelan music is very different to anything you've seen before. If you are interested to learn about a different musical style, even a different way of thinking about what music is and why you create it, then I would recommend taking this class. Also, because it is quite a different style, it is also quite accessible to students who have no/little training in Western music.

I would for sure recommend this course to another student. It is an opportunity to learn to play an instrument that you don't need any experience with in a manner that introduces you to a culture, music, and context that for many students at Yale is new; proving to be a worth while and rewarding challenge.
